Good — I checked how colordx handles `lighten`/`darken`. Important finding:

```
d20: oklch(0.301 0.049 48.35)
d20.darken(0.05):  oklch(0.246 0.037 48.60)  ← chroma changed!
d20.lighten(0.075): oklch(0.379 0.066 48.11)  ← chroma changed!
```

colordx's lighten/darken **don't preserve chroma or hue** — they shift all three. The original hand-tuned classic values kept chroma nearly constant (~0.05) across the dark range. So your idea of specifying numeric luma/chroma/hue parameters is actually **more faithful** to the original design intent than using `.lighten()`/`.darken()`.

Here are three takes on your scoped-per-range idea:

---

## 1) Your idea — numeric params per range

```ts
const primaries = createPrimaryScale({
    darks: {
        base: { luma: 0.301, chroma: 0.049, hue: 48.35 },
        spread: 0.075,
        overrides: (gen) => ({
            d10: gen.d20.darken(0.05),            // tighter dark
            d20: colordx("oklch(0.301 0.049 48.35)"), // same as gen
        }),
    },
    mids: [
        colordx("oklch(0.483 0.075 48.75)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.569 0.074 49.6)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.655 0.075 48.42)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.742 0.075 49.01)"),
    ],
    lights: {
        base: { luma: 0.825, chroma: 0.055, hue: 60 },
        spread: 0.075,
    },
});
```

The function generates d20 from the base params, derives d30/d40 via chained `lighten(spread)`, defaults d10 to `d20.darken(spread)` (gen.d20.darken(0.075)), then `overrides` replaces d10 with `d20.darken(0.05)`. Mids are fully explicit.

---

## 2) Simpler — pass Colordx objects, keep range-scoped overrides

Same structure but you pass the anchor as a Colordx instead of numeric params:

```ts
const primaries = createPrimaryScale({
    darks: {
        d20: colordx("oklch(0.301 0.049 48.35)"),
        spread: 0.075,
        overrides: (gen) => ({
            d10: gen.d20.darken(0.05),
        }),
    },
    mids: [
        colordx("oklch(0.483 0.075 48.75)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.569 0.074 49.6)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.655 0.075 48.42)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.742 0.075 49.01)"),
    ],
    lights: {
        l10: colordx("oklch(0.825 0.055 60)"),
        spread: 0.075,
    },
});
```

Less verbose but still scoped. The spread is shared per range.

---

## 3) Mixed — darks/lights use params, mids are explicit

The sweet spot. The formulaic ranges (darks, lights) use numeric oklch — clear, concise, and you control chroma/hue. The hand-tuned mids are just an array.

```ts
const primaries = createPrimaryScale({
    darks: { luma: 0.301, chroma: 0.049, hue: 48.35, spread: 0.075 },
    mids: [
        colordx("oklch(0.483 0.075 48.75)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.569 0.074 49.6)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.655 0.075 48.42)"),
        colordx("oklch(0.742 0.075 49.01)"),
    ],
    lights: { luma: 0.825, chroma: 0.055, hue: 60, spread: 0.075 },
}, {
    overrides: (gen) => ({
        d10: gen.d20.darken(0.05),   // non-standard spread
    }),
});
```

Top-level overrides since they're exceptional anyway.

---

Which direction feels closest to what you had in mind? I'm leaning toward **#1** or **#3** — the numeric params keep the oklch values visible in the definition (that's the "soul" of the theme) without needing to construct `colordx()` calls for every generated value.

